messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

Not sure what was changed, from the differences.

Patch Set 1:

It is not possible for me to understand the changes.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think, we shall be using POSTMAN variables as much as possible.
See URLs, they contain specific IP addresses valid in a single environment...

This shall be converted to variables, and variables shall be defined in a collection.
Cover all possible places, where variables could be used (URL is evident, but I see as well certain possibilities in the requests body)

Patch Set 1:

Hi Martin/Alex/Damian,I will have Santanu explain the differences. Obviously, because it is Postman, he does not have control over what it might generate as diffs.

To the point of using variables, the idea of providing these scripts was meant to show how a model could be validated. It was never mean to *be* the way to validate the Fronthaul interface.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Hi Martin/Alex/Damian,I will have Santanu explain the differences. Obviously, because it is Postman, he does not have control over what it might generate as diffs.
> 
> To the point of using variables, the idea of providing these scripts was meant to show how a model could be validated. It was never mean to *be* the way to validate the Fronthaul interface.

Well, this has little to do with variables actually.
If that collection shall serve as a reference for anything, then it would be nice to make sure, that it could be re-used in different environment. Variables are the way to make that easier.

If the intention is to demonstrate a real-world example, then the question would be - shall this really be a code in a repository? Maybe a Confluence page is better, especially, if You don`t intendt to modify this collection later on...?

Patch Set 5:

The container release file needs to be reverted back to the original contents.  The job that is failing (#6) shouldn't be triggered until after the change is merged and that container version exists.  The "logic" is that the change merges, and generates a new image in the repo, and then the container-release file is modified, and committed.  That causes the jenkins job to kick which moves the image from staging to release.  The beef it has right now is that it cannot find the "next" image to move because it hasn't been created.

The process has always seemed strange to me, and I don't like having to add commits to "push" the images round, but it is what it is.

I'm still trying to sort the other issue, but figured I'd pass this along now.
